[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Ortiz Rock is a delightful 83-year-old resident of South Carolina Des Moines, Iowa who is an avid skier, engineer, and industrialist, who presents to us referred by Dr. Thames for an opinion with regard to postoperative approaches to this patient with recently resected cecal tumor with pathology pending, but deemed most consistent with lymph node-positive adenocarcinoma of the colon.  Historically, Mr. Rock presented with some fatigue, shortness-of-breath, and anemia with a hemoglobin decreased to 8.6 g/dL ultimately leading to blood transfusion and colonoscopy identifying concerning area around the splenic flexure.  A right colonic circumferential cecal area mass was identified and resected by Dr. Thames, and we are seeing the patient in the wake of his recent surgery.
From a symptomatic standpoint, Mr. Rock was doing well, convalescing, and had no new complaints.  He was content with his progress.
Past medical history in Mr. Rock is significant for a mastectomy related to breast cancer.  This has been nonrecurrent.
